docs.abstract: I briefly got my hands on Apple’s new high-tech goggles, which impressed and creeped me out and raised a question: Why do we need these?
docs.snippet: I briefly got my hands on Apple’s new high-tech goggles, which impressed and creeped me out and raised a question: Why do we need these?
docs.lead_paragraph: I got a sneak peek into Apple’s vision for the future of computing on Monday. For about half an hour, I wore the $3,500 Vision Pro, the company’s first high-tech goggles, which will be released next year.

headline.main: A First Try of Apple’s $3,500 Vision Pro Headset

docs.abstract: The secretary of state’s talks with Xi Jinping raised hopes that the world’s two biggest economies might stabilize relations, but the big challenges were not resolved.
docs.snippet: The secretary of state’s talks with Xi Jinping raised hopes that the world’s two biggest economies might stabilize relations, but the big challenges were not resolved.
docs.lead_paragraph: Worries about China’s economic recovery sent stocks and U.S. futures lower on Tuesday morning, despite a promising meeting on Monday between the country’s top leader, Xi Jinping, and Secretary of State Antony Blinken in Beijing.

headline.main: Business Lessons From Blinken’s Trip to China

byline.original: By Andrew Ross Sorkin, Ravi Mattu, Bernhard Warner, Sarah Kessler, Michael J. de la Merced, Lauren Hirsch and Ephrat Livni

docs.abstract: Interest in the futuristic, immersive digital world is fading just as Apple plans to debut a virtual reality device.
docs.snippet: Interest in the futuristic, immersive digital world is fading just as Apple plans to debut a virtual reality device.
docs.lead_paragraph: Mark Zuckerberg embraced a digital world known as the metaverse when he said in November 2021 that he was changing his company’s name from Facebook to Meta.

headline.main: Apple Is Stepping Into the Metaverse. Will Anyone Care?
headline.print_headline: Apple Is Stepping Into the Metaverse. Will Anyone Want to Follow?

byline.original: By Kellen Browning and Mike Isaac

docs.abstract: The iPhone maker is making a bold bet that it can redefine the niche category of virtual reality with its $3,500 goggles.
docs.snippet: The iPhone maker is making a bold bet that it can redefine the niche category of virtual reality with its $3,500 goggles.
docs.lead_paragraph: It’s here (or it will be “early next year”): Apple unveiled its long-awaited entry into virtual reality, or what the tech giant calls “spatial computing,” in the form of the Apple Vision Pro, a $3,500 device that looks like exquisitely designed futuristic ski goggles.

headline.main: Can Apple Take the Metaverse Mainstream?

byline.original: By Andrew Ross Sorkin, Ravi Mattu, Bernhard Warner, Sarah Kessler, Michael J. de la Merced, Lauren Hirsch and Ephrat Livni

docs.abstract: Chief executives in the U.S. have long pushed for closer ties between the two countries. Now they just hope a rocky situation won’t get worse.
docs.snippet: Chief executives in the U.S. have long pushed for closer ties between the two countries. Now they just hope a rocky situation won’t get worse.
docs.lead_paragraph: In a meeting in Beijing on Friday, China’s leader, Xi Jinping, traded warm smiles with Bill Gates and praised Mr. Gates as “the first American friend” he had met this year.

headline.main: As U.S. and Chinese Officials Meet, Businesses Temper Their Hopes
headline.print_headline: Modest Hopes as Blinken Heads to China

byline.original: By Ana Swanson and David McCabe

docs.abstract: India’s fast-growing economy is drawing American corporate giants, even as the country faces scrutiny over ties to Russia and limits on political freedoms.
docs.snippet: India’s fast-growing economy is drawing American corporate giants, even as the country faces scrutiny over ties to Russia and limits on political freedoms.
docs.lead_paragraph: The White House is rolling out the red carpet for Narendra Modi, India’s prime minister, with a state dinner on Thursday. High on the agenda: Talks to strengthen economic and security ties as the Biden administration cultivates partners to counter China. Business is watching closely, too, as it pours money into one of the world’s fastest-growing big economies despite the challenges of operating there.

headline.main: Business Leaders Join Biden in Welcoming Modi to the U.S.

byline.original: By Andrew Ross Sorkin, Ravi Mattu, Bernhard Warner, Sarah Kessler, Michael J. de la Merced, Lauren Hirsch and Ephrat Livni

docs.abstract: This isn’t the first time Apple has introduced a bulky piece of hardware that nobody is sure people will want to buy. Can Apple pull off another wearable revolution?
docs.snippet: This isn’t the first time Apple has introduced a bulky piece of hardware that nobody is sure people will want to buy. Can Apple pull off another wearable revolution?
docs.lead_paragraph: Apple kicked off the week with the announcement of a mixed-reality headset: the Apple Vision Pro. Putting a computer on your face may seem weird, but if there’s one company that knows how to make nerdy stuff into the thing that everyone wants, it’s Apple. Will these fancy goggles be the next Apple revolution?

headline.main: Apple’s Face Computer, Crypto Chaos and How Teens Really Feel About Social Media

byline.original: By Kevin Roose, Casey Newton, Davis Land, Rachel Cohn, Jen Poyant, Corey Schreppel, Dan Powell, Elisheba Ittoop, Marion Lozano, Sophia Lanman and Rowan Niemisto

docs.abstract: Newly announced modifications to the autocorrect feature used on iPhones will better understand a word’s context in a text message, saving users some blushes.
docs.snippet: Newly announced modifications to the autocorrect feature used on iPhones will better understand a word’s context in a text message, saving users some blushes.
docs.lead_paragraph: Apple on Monday announced an updated autocorrect function that aims to more accurately reflect users’ intended word choices, pleasing customers whose attempts to swear in texts have long been replaced with “duck” or “ducking” (and freeing innocent waterfowl from their unfortunate association with an obscenity).

headline.main: Apple Knows You Didn’t Mean to Type ‘Ducking’
headline.print_headline: Apple Admits ‘Duck’ Isn’t What You Typed

docs.abstract: A complex arrangement, involving Apple, to bring the soccer star to Miami shows how to trump the free-spending kingdom — and how hard that may be to duplicate.
docs.snippet: A complex arrangement, involving Apple, to bring the soccer star to Miami shows how to trump the free-spending kingdom — and how hard that may be to duplicate.
docs.lead_paragraph: Just a day after Saudi Arabia claimed a huge win in sports — an agreement to merge the PGA Tour with its own upstart golf circuit, LIV — the kingdom suffered a stinging defeat: It fell short in its quest to land Lionel Messi, one of soccer’s all-time greats.

headline.main: How the Lionel Messi Deal Stymied Saudi Arabia

byline.original: By Andrew Ross Sorkin, Ravi Mattu, Bernhard Warner, Sarah Kessler, Michael J. de la Merced, Lauren Hirsch and Ephrat Livni

docs.abstract: Apple says its new Vision Pro headset will “shift the way we look at technology.” How about how we look?
docs.snippet: Apple says its new Vision Pro headset will “shift the way we look at technology.” How about how we look?
docs.lead_paragraph: They talked about the optics. They talked about the computer specs. They talked about the “lenticular glass” and the “new spatial computing platform” and the “aluminum alloy” used in the “primary structural element.”

headline.print_headline: Envision What You Might Look Like
